{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"1300496e-c3d9-424a-a9c4-5669cf19b301","content":"Here's my analysis:\n\n## Root Cause\n\nThe report confirms the overhead isn't compilation — it's **MSBuild process startup and project re-evaluation** on every `dotnet build` invocation. Visual Studio avoids this by keeping a long-lived MSBuild server in-process.\n\n## Recommendations (most to least impactful)\n\n### 1. Use `dotnet watch build` for the inner loop\nKeeps the host process alive and watches for changes — eliminates startup cost entirely:\n```\ndotnet watch build\n```\n\n### 2. Enable the MSBuild Build Server (.NET 8+)\nReuses an MSBuild server process across CLI invocations, just like VS does:\n```bash\nexport DOTNET_CLI_USE_MSBUILD_SERVER=1\ndotnet build\n```\nOr set it permanently in the project:\n```xml\n<PropertyGroup>\n  <MSBuildServer>true</MSBuildServer>\n</PropertyGroup>\n```\n\n### 3. Use the Terminal Logger (`-tl`)\nThe .NET 8 terminal logger implicitly leverages the MSBuild server:\n```\ndotnet build -tl\n```\n\n### 4. Verify MSBuild Node Reuse isn't disabled\nEnsure neither of these are set in your environment, as they kill worker node caching:\n```bash\n# These should NOT be set:\n#   MSBUILDDISABLENODEREUSE=1\n#   DOTNET_CLI_DO_NOT_USE_MSBUILD_SERVER=1\n```\n\n### Summary\n\n| Approach | Startup cost | Best for |\n|---|---|---|\n| `dotnet watch build` | **Zero** (persistent) | Edit-build-test loop |\n| `DOTNET_CLI_USE_MSBUILD_SERVER=1` | **~200ms** (warm server) | Ad-hoc CLI builds |\n| `-tl` | **~200ms** (warm server) | Quick one-off builds |\n\nFor the fastest inner loop, **`dotnet watch build`** is the clear winner — it mirrors what VS does by keeping the build infrastructure warm.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"df66bf4e-38e4-4ea3-aeb3-708e279e4f6c","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The developer reports that `dotnet build` from the CLI is slow for incremental builds (2-4 seconds even when nothing changed), while Visual Studio rebuilds nearly instantly. They've already verified:\n- No analyzers slowing things down\n- Incremental build targets are working\n- The project compiles in <500ms\n\nThe overhead is from MSBuild process startup and re-evaluation of the project graph on every CLI invocation.\n\nThe key insight here is that Visual Studio uses a persistent MSBuild server process, so it doesn't pay the startup cost on every build. The CLI, by default, starts a new MSBuild process each time.\n\nThere are several recommendations I can make:\n\n\n- Enable the MSBuild server with `DOTNET_CLI_USE_MSBUILD_SERVER=1` or the `-tl` flag to reuse processes across builds\n- Use `dotnet watch` for the edit-build-test loop, which keeps the process alive and performs true incremental builds\n- Try graph-based builds with the `-graph` flag to help MSBuild optimize the build graph evaluation\n\nThe real bottleneck here is the startup overhead of spawning a new MSBuild process on each invocation. The most practical fix is using `dotnet watch build` to eliminate that cost entirely during development, or enabling the MSBuild server in .NET 8+ with the environment variable. Now I'm ready to lay out some concrete steps to improve the build performance.","outputTokens":1223,"requestId":"0404:913B3:421D0B:4D67E2:69F0041F"},"id":"55dacfb1-e209-4b14-b5b8-177c57c54a0b","timestamp":"2026-04-28T00:50:00.378Z","parentId":"dcb83f07-2397-44ee-8c5f-78498743b65b"}
